According to The World Health Organization (WHO) close to 800 000 people die by suicide every year. Furthermore, for each suicide, there are more than 20 suicide attempts. Suicides and suicide attempts have a ripple effect that impacts on families, friends, colleagues, communities and societies. Suicides are preventable. Much can be done to prevent suicide at individual, community and national levels. So, comes my intuition to inspect the similarities between the nations in committing suicides to give some indicator on how to prevent them

  • suicides/100k pop : This column represents the number of death by suicide out of total of 100.000 deaths. You can think of it as percentage but with a base 100.000 instead of 100.
  • HDI for year : It stands for the the Human Development Index for the year. It's between 0 and 1. Higher values represent higher life quality (education, health, and income )
  • gdp_for_year ($) : It stands for the the Gross Domestic Product (the amount of wealth produced in the country in one year).

In [66]:
def correlation_plot(data, year):
    df = data[data["year"] == year].drop(columns = "year").copy()
    sns.heatmap(
    df.groupby("country").agg("sum").corr(), cmap = "viridis", annot = True)
    plt.title(f"Correlation among numeric variables in {year}")
    plt.show();
plt.figure(figsize= (5, 3))
correlation_plot(data, 1985)
correlation_plot(data, 2014)

In [68]:
def plot_scatter_links(x:str, y:str, years:list, 
                       agg_fun = "sum", n_col = None):
    
    df = data[data["year"].isin(years)]
    
    df = df.groupby(["year", "country"]).agg(agg_fun).reset_index()
    df["year"] = df["year"].dt.year.astype("object")
    sns.lmplot(x, y, scatter = True, fit_reg= True, 
               data = df, col = "year", col_wrap = n_col, sharex = False, sharey = False)
    
plot_scatter_links(x = "gdp_per_capita ($)", y = "suicides/100k pop", 
                   years = ["1985","1995", "2005", "2015"], n_col= 2, agg_fun= "mean")
plt.subplots_adjust(top=.9)
plt.suptitle("link between  Suicide and GDP/capita", size = 30);

I'm adding a new column called occurence which gives tha value 1 to every row so that whenever we group and sum the numeric data we can come back to the original data by dividing it.

data["part_generation"] = 0

new_data["year"] = new_data["year"].dt.year

K-Means¶
In [73]:
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
inertia =[] 
for k in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=0).fit(x)
    preds = kmeans.predict(x)
    inertia.append(silhouette_score(x, preds))
ax = plt.plot(range(2,10),inertia)
plt.suptitle(" K-Means", size = 30);
GaussianMixture¶
In [74]:
from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture
inertia =[] 
for k in range(2, 10):
    clusterer = GaussianMixture(n_components = k)
    clusterer.fit(x)
    preds = clusterer.predict(x)
    inertia.append(silhouette_score(x, preds))
    
ax = plt.plot(range(2,10),inertia)
plt.suptitle("GaussianMixture", size = 30);

iI k means at 3 clusters gives the best score than GaussianMixture with 7 clusters¶
